{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507103"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:49:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:49:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2601"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2601"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.25,0.48,0.19,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34170"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2601"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19343"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"9359"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8618"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8633"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40758"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44870"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/34170"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents with a 6-month history of persistent headaches and progressive weakness in his lower limbs. The patient reports that the headaches are mostly located at the back of the head and worsen with coughing or straining. On examination, the patient is found to have weakness in his lower limbs with hyperreflexia, and Babinski\u0027s sign is present bilaterally. An MRI of the brain and spinal cord was performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Observation and symptomatic management","Medical management with corticosteroids","Surgical decompression","Ventriculoperitoneal shunting","Radiotherapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with an Arnold Chiari malformation as indicated by the signs and symptoms along with the presence of a hypoplastic posterior cranial fossa, herniated cerebellar tonsils, syringomyelia (spinal cord cystic lesions) and bulbomyelia (brain stem cystic lesions) on the MRI (Image). \u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical decompression \u003C/strong\u003Eof the cerebellar tonsils is the primary management option for Arnold Chiari malformation. The goal of surgery is to alleviate pressure on the cerebellum, brainstem, and spinal cord by removing the cerebellar tonsils or widening the foramen magnum. This can prevent or reverse neurological symptoms and prevent further complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArnold Chiari malformation is a structural problem and \u003Cstrong\u003Eobservation alone along with symptomatic management \u003C/strong\u003Ecan resolve the symptoms but is unlikely to resolve the underlying problem causing the symptoms or prevent progression of the disease. Observation is only appropriate with asymptomatic presentation. The motor weakness necessitates surgical intervention being offered. as does the very typical cough headaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedical management with corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E has been shown to be effective in reducing inflammation and nerve root compression in certain conditions but is not indicated for Arnold Chiari malformation since this is a structural problem not inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentriculoperitoneal shunting\u003C/strong\u003E is not a primary management option for Arnold Chiari malformation. Although syringomyelia is a known complication of Arnold Chiari malformation, it is not an indication for ventriculoperitoneal shunting. If shunting is required this is syringo- pleural shunt typically. This is not a first line management \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate  management option for Arnold Chiari malformation and is not indicated for symptomatic relief. Instead, surgical decompression of the cerebellar tonsils is the most appropriate management option for patients with Arnold Chiari malformation presenting with neurological symptoms such as headaches and lower limb weakness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Surgical decompression is the management of choice in a patient with Arnold Chiari malformation presenting with neurological symptoms."],"references":["Hidalgo JA, Tork CA, Varacallo M. Arnold Chiari Malformation. [Updated 2022 Sep 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-.","Batzdorf U, McArthur DL, Bentson JR. Surgical treatment of Chiari malformation with and without syringomyelia: experience with 177 adult patients. J Neurosurg. 2013 Feb;118(2):232-42. doi: 10.3171/2012.10.JNS12305. Epub 2012 Nov 23. PMID: 23176335."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19343"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2601"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19658"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19658"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1b70a84d-e883-4cfd-9528-18bdc7ad7dcc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1b70a84d-e883-4cfd-9528-18bdc7ad7dcc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":620,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19343"